00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:09.640
Jonathan Rucker was a
black doctor who take

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:13.510
of the 500 troops in
the supply train.

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:17.040
Doug got to know five
of Rucker's 10 children,

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:21.680
even setting up a Rucker family
reunion in Natchez, Mississippi.

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:24.700
In 2009 I entered Doug's life.

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:26.000
I met his family.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.080
Then I met the Rucker family.

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:29.540
I knew something of World War I.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:32.150
I'd been a history teacher and two

00:06:32.150 --> 00:06:35.520
of my grandparents had
been involved in the war.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:39.730
My grandfather was a sergeant
with the 77th Division,

00:06:39.730 --> 00:06:42.540
a teamster with the artillery unit.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:46.500
My grandmother was a nurse at
Saint Vincent's in New York,

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:50.850
and she took care of
the returning wounded.

00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:54.920
She didn't want any of us to
go into nursing after that.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:59.620
Doug wanted to write
Rucker's biography.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:03.700
But it was a good story,
but I could not believe

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.700
that Rucker was the only doctor.

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:08.600
The Army just doesn't do ones.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:13.920 position:56%
So, we went to Fort Des Moines where
Rucker trained to find out more.

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:18.330
No one, including the curator
at Fort Des Moines Museum,

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:22.340
where the physicians received their
basic training knew their names

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:25.620 position:56%
or even how many of them there were.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.600
We spent months combing
through the files here

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:32.330
at National Archives
before the eureka moment

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:35.480
and the discovery of the list.

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:41.530 position:56%
It was in an ancient folder of the
U.S. Army Surgeon General's records;

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:45.890
so old that the identification
tab had disintegrated.

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:51.340
It as typed by some clerk 100
years ago on many sheets of paper

00:07:51.340 --> 00:07:55.440
with columns of information;
hometowns, medical schools,

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:58.490
graduation years and ages.

00:07:58.490 --> 00:08:01.550
The sheets were then glued together

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:06.300
and the resulting document was
four feet long and 18 inches wide.

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:09.110
And then it had been
folded in and in,

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:12.930
until it fit into a standard file.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:17.630
One hundred years ago, the United
States was largely a country

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:21.430
of racial segregation,
discrimination,

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:24.180
lynching and Jim Crow laws.

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:30.090
These 104 men were among the
nations estimated 1500 African

00:08:30.090 --> 00:08:32.100
American doctors.

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:36.230
They had succeeded in gaining
advanced education and training

00:08:36.230 --> 00:08:38.440
at a time when it was problematic

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:43.400
for any African American
to achieve such success.

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:47.650
Yet they answered their country's
call and left their practices

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:50.520
to provide medical care
for the fighting men

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:54.290
of the 92nd and the 93rd Divisions.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:56.510
Sixty percent of these doctors came

00:08:56.510 --> 00:09:00.240
from just three African
American medical schools.

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.360
The largest contingent
were graduates

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:06.340
of two Tennessee medical schools.

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:10.830
Thirty four from Meharry Medical
School in Nashville and eight

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:14.630
from the University of
West Tennessee in Memphis.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:20.310 position:56%
But 16 came from Howard in D.C.
Thirteen from Leonard Medical School

00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:25.240
at Shaw University in
Raleigh, two went to Harvard,

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:28.950
three from the University of
Illinois, two from the University

00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:34.170
of Michigan, and two from
Northwestern Medical School.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:36.480
Why would they enlist?

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:39.150
They expected times
would be different.

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:43.550
After the war, they thought they'd
be recognized for their service.

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:47.260
They thought all men of
their race would benefit.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:50.200
But nothing changed after the war.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:53.890
But some of, many of these
men would become the leaders

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:58.440
of their communities and
organizations like the NAACP

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:01.760
that would make racial
equality possible.

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:04.330
So we had to tell their stories.

00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:09.120
We spent the next five years
at the Library of Congress,

00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:12.250
the National Archives,
numerous state

00:10:12.250 --> 00:10:15.710
and city historical
associations, libraries,

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:18.540
and with a variety
of newspaper sources.

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:21.520
We met the children
and the grandchildren

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.050
of these extraordinary men.

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:30.640
Initially we wrote four historical
journals and spoke to small groups.

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:36.070
Then, after a chance meeting with
Professor Henry Louis Gates, Jr.,

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:40.480
in the elevator of Hay-Adams
Hotel in Washington, well,

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:45.210
actually what happened was we had
gone to a wedding the night before.

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:47.440
And we were coming down
to go to breakfast.

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:52.100
We got out of the elevator and we
saw Henry Louis Gates checking in.

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:55.250
So we stepped over to
the side and we waited

00:10:55.250 --> 00:10:57.010
until he got in the elevator.

00:10:57.010 --> 00:10:59.010
And then we jumped in with him.

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:02.160
And we started talking as
fast as we possibly could.

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:04.220
And so, he said, "What
is this, a hustle?"

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:06.790
And we said, Doug said,
"Absolutely."

00:11:06.790 --> 00:11:11.350
So, we told him about the
project and so he had us, he said,

00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:15.770
I don't have a card, but here,
I'll repeat my email address.

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:17.600
I want you to send me one.

00:11:17.600 --> 00:11:18.900
And so, we did.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:22.520
And in the subject line
we put, Hay-Adams Hustle.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:25.280
It was a Sunday we sent it.

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:26.580
Monday, we heard from him.

00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:28.690
He hired us to write 15 of them.

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:31.100
So, he wanted shorter ones.

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:32.730
We're still writing for him.

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:35.180
We're still doing shorter
biographies

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:40.010
for his African American
National biography.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:43.650
We did this and then
the book came next.

00:11:43.650 --> 00:11:49.560 position:56%
And now Doug will talk about the
Army in 1917, as we entered the war.

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:55.300
